{"accepted":[{"assertion":"AI-contributions wiki claim — wiki: Various partial results.","id":"vf_4cc96a02414236a1","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Formal-Conjectures statement: Erdos686.erdos_686 https://google-deepmind.github.io/formal-conjectures/theorem/?name=Erdos686.erdos_686.","id":"vf_d0a52486e0f0a98e","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Erdős Problem #686: declared status 'open'. Formalized: yes. Can every integer $N\\geq 2$ be written as\\[N=\\frac{\\prod_{1\\leq i\\leq k}(m+i)}{\\prod_{1\\leq i\\leq k}(n+i)}\\]for some $k\\geq 2$ and $m\\geq n+k$? Prize: no. Tags: number theory.","id":"vf_d8218ce87084620c","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"}],"accepted_activity":false,"activity":[{"accepted":false,"banked":true,"claim":"Erdos #686: lean/Vela/Erdos686.lean (kernel-checked, axiom-clean, no sorry) proves the k=2 and k=4 obstructions for prime-power squares. If A is a prime power then A^2 has no representation N=prod_{i<=k}(m+i)/prod_{i<=k}(n+i) (m>=n+k) with k=2 or k=4 -- in particular N=4 has none -- via prime-power divisibility (no multiple of A lies strictly between consecutive multiples A*N0 and A*(N0+1)) plus a general k=4 => k=2 reduction with the same multiplier ((t+1)..(t+4)=4*(u+1)(u+2)). This is theorem-grade partial progress; it does NOT address k=3, k>=5, or composite non-prime-power square N.","claimed_status":"verified_computationally","classification":"legacy_attempt","id":"vat_a12eb8361af0b99a","kind":"partial_proof","lifecycle":"banked","location":"current_commit","mathematical_scope":"partial","method_channel":"erdos-problems","method_families":[],"named_obstructions":[],"related_problems":[],"remaining_obligations":["lean/Vela/Erdos686.lean"],"source_ref":"frontier.json#vat_a12eb8361af0b99a","trust":"signed"},{"accepted":false,"claim":"Pinned Formal Conjectures activity classification; integration activity does not establish mathematical truth.","id":"activity:fc-mathematical_proof_work:686","kind":